{"parse":{"title":"Affect in education","pageid":37237169,"revid":854623037,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-style ambox-Orphan\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"display: none\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Wiki_letter_w.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Wiki letter w.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/40px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"40\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/60px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/80px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"44\" data-file-height=\"44\" /></a></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>is an <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Orphan\" title=\"Wikipedia:Orphan\">orphan</a>, as no other articles <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Whatlinkshere&amp;target=Affect_in_education&amp;namespace=0\">link to it</a></b>. Please <a href=\"/wiki/Help:Link\" title=\"Help:Link\">introduce links</a> to this page from <span class=\"plainlinks\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special%3ASearch&amp;redirs=1&amp;search=Affect+in+education&amp;fulltext=Search&amp;ns0=1&amp;title=Special%3ASearch&amp;advanced=1&amp;fulltext=Affect+in+education\">related articles</a></span>; try the <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//edwardbetts.com/find_link?q=Affect_in_education\">Find link tool</a> for suggestions.  <small><i>(December 2013)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The importance of <b>affect in education</b> has become a topic of increasing interest in the fields of <a href=\"/wiki/Psychology\" title=\"Psychology\">psychology</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Education\" title=\"Education\">education</a>. It is a commonly held opinion that curriculum and emotional literacy should be interwoven. Examples of such curriculum include using English language to increase emotional vocabulary, and writing about the self and history to discuss emotion in major events such as <a href=\"/wiki/Genocide\" title=\"Genocide\">genocide</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Hayes2009_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hayes2009-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> This type of curriculum is also known as therapeutic education. According to Ecclestone and Hayes, therapeutic education focuses on the emotional over the intellectual.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Hayes2009_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hayes2009-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Educator_attitudes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Educator attitudes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#School_attitudes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">School attitudes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Funding\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Funding</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Criticisms\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Criticisms</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Educator_attitudes\">Educator attitudes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Affect_in_education&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Educator attitudes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In order for such curriculum to be implemented, it is essential that educators be aware of the importance emotional literacy. Examination of educator and student attitudes towards emotional literacy is a common topic of research. Researchers have found that staff have conceptions of what constitutes emotional literacy, including being self-aware of one\u2019s own feelings, using emotional language, and being cognizant that children have feelings that need to be taken into account.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In addition, staff discussed the necessity of having all educators dedicated to creating an emotionally literate school, and the detrimental effects of even one educator not supporting this initiative.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"School_attitudes\">School attitudes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Affect_in_education&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: School attitudes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Roffey (2008) examined the influence of emotional literacy on the school as a whole using <a href=\"/wiki/Ecological_study\" title=\"Ecological study\">ecological analysis</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> It was found that positive change was gradual, and involved multiple elements. For instance, teachers who felt as though they were genuinely valued and were consulted about policy felt happier at work. In turn, these teachers felt better prepared to handle conflicts that arose inside the classroom, and when students experienced this positive approach they were more cooperative. This shows how incorporating emotional literacy into a child's education is a school-wide collaborative effort.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Funding\">Funding</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Affect_in_education&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Funding\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Examples of government funding of emotional literacy include <a href=\"/wiki/Every_Child_Matters\" title=\"Every Child Matters\">Every Child Matters</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Criticisms\">Criticisms</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Affect_in_education&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Criticisms\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Criticisms of educational literacy in curriculum revolves around the idea that it although well intended, it is designed to disempower students.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Affect_in_education&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Hayes2009-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Hayes2009_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Hayes2009_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Ecclestone, Kathryn; Hayes (June 2009). \"Changing the subject: The educational implications of developing emotional well-being\". <i>Oxford Review of Education</i>. <b>35</b> (3): 371\u2013389. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1080/03054980902934662\">10.1080/03054980902934662</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Oxford+Review+of+Education&amp;rft.atitle=Changing+the+subject%3A+The+educational+implications+of+developing+emotional+well-being&amp;rft.volume=35&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=371-389&amp;rft.date=2009-06&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1080%2F03054980902934662&amp;rft.aulast=Ecclestone&amp;rft.aufirst=Kathryn&amp;rft.au=Hayes&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAffect+in+education\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Perry, Lorraine; Lennie, C.; Humphrey, N. (2008). \"Emotional literacy in the primary classroom: teacher perceptions and practices\". <i>Education 3-13</i>. 1. <b>36</b> (1): 27\u201337. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1080/03004270701576851\">10.1080/03004270701576851</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Education+3-13&amp;rft.atitle=Emotional+literacy+in+the+primary+classroom%3A+teacher+perceptions+and+practices&amp;rft.volume=36&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=27-37&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1080%2F03004270701576851&amp;rft.aulast=Perry&amp;rft.aufirst=Lorraine&amp;rft.au=Lennie%2C+C.&amp;rft.au=Humphrey%2C+N.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAffect+in+education\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Roffey, Sue (2007). \"Transformation and Emotional Literacy: The role of school leaders in developing a caring community\". <i>Leading &amp; Managing</i>. <b>13</b> (1): 16\u201330.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Leading+%26+Managing&amp;rft.atitle=Transformation+and+Emotional+Literacy%3A+The+role+of+school+leaders+in+developing+a+caring+community&amp;rft.volume=13&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=16-30&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.aulast=Roffey&amp;rft.aufirst=Sue&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAffect+in+education\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Ecclestone, Kathryn; Hayes, Dennis (2009). <i>The dangerous rise of therapeutic education</i>. New York, NY: Routledge. pp.&#160;vii. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-203-87056-5\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-203-87056-5\">0-203-87056-5</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+dangerous+rise+of+therapeutic+education&amp;rft.place=New+York%2C+NY&amp;rft.pages=vii&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=0-203-87056-5&amp;rft.aulast=Ecclestone&amp;rft.aufirst=Kathryn&amp;rft.au=Hayes%2C+Dennis&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAffect+in+education\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2140\nCached time